%N A090679 Integer part of the hypotenuse of a right triangle with twin prime legs.
%C A090679 The real value of these numbers is irrational. If x,x+2 are a twin prime pair then x is odd. Assume x^2 + (x+2)^2 = a^2/b^2 for integers a,b such that (a,b)=1. Since x is odd = 2*m+1 we have 4*m^2 + 4*m + 1 + 4*m^2 + 12*m + 9 = 8*m^2 + 16*m + 10 = a^2/b^2. Multiplying by b^2 we get 8*m^2*b^2 + 16*m*b^2 + 10*b^2 = a^2 => a is even = 2*k. So 8*m^2*b^2 + 16*m*b^2 + 10*b^2 = 4*k^2 or 4*m^2*b^2 + 8*m*b^2 + 5*b^2 = 2*k. This implies b is even contrary to a being even (a,b)=1. Therefore sqrt(x^2 + (x+2)^2) is irrational and all twin prime pair legs of a right triangle form an irrational hypotenuse.
%H A090679 Harvey P. Dale, <a href="/A090679/b090679.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%t A090679 f[n_] := IntegerPart[ Sqrt[2 n^2 + 4 n + 4]]; f[ Select[ Prime@ Range@ 250, PrimeQ[# + 2] &]] (* _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 10 2013 *)
%t A090679 Floor[Sqrt[Total[#]]]&/@(Select[Partition[Prime[Range[300]],2,1], Last[#]- First[#] == 2&]^2) (* _Harvey P. Dale_, Jun 07 2014 *)
%o A090679 (PARI) /* Twin right triangles */ twinright(n) = { forprime(x=3,n, y=x+2; if(isprime(y), print1(sqrtint(x^2+y^2)", ") ) ) }
